00:00:22,530 --> 00:00:26,790
But the big question is, well, what is a wireframe?

9
00:00:27,240 --> 00:00:33,420
Now, you may have seen images like this when we were sketching, and wireframe is a low fidelity layout

10
00:00:33,420 --> 00:00:36,120
that serves three simple purposes.

11
00:00:36,120 --> 00:00:40,380
It presents the information that will be displayed on the page in a little bit more detail than our

12
00:00:40,380 --> 00:00:42,360
sketches and our user flows.

13
00:00:42,780 --> 00:00:49,590
It gives an outline of structure and layout of the page, and it conveys the overall direction and description

14
00:00:49,590 --> 00:00:51,210
of your user interface.

15
00:00:51,240 --> 00:00:57,720
It's basically, as you can see here, it's just like a blueprint of a building, but instead of a building,

16
00:00:57,720 --> 00:01:02,730
it describes the details clearly and specifically, while giving everyone involved a good overview of

17
00:01:02,730 --> 00:01:03,540
the product.

18
00:01:04,110 --> 00:01:09,630
It's kind of like that middle ground between your sketches and higher fidelity designs and prototypes.

19
00:01:09,630 --> 00:01:15,990
They help you really plan layout interaction patterns for your users without worrying about distracting

20
00:01:15,990 --> 00:01:19,530
details like colors or copy or, you know, typography.

21
00:01:19,530 --> 00:01:22,470
You know, all those things can really bog down your design process.

22
00:01:23,490 --> 00:01:29,370
Another thing to really know is that they're really heavily influenced from your prior work.

23
00:01:29,370 --> 00:01:36,150
So if you've done story mapping, you have user stories, if you've done things like user flows or site

24
00:01:36,150 --> 00:01:41,190
maps, I mean, all these different artifacts should really influence the way you create your wireframes.

25
00:01:41,190 --> 00:01:46,740
So just keep that in mind that you shouldn't just be like jumping in and creating a whole bunch of wireframes

26
00:01:46,740 --> 00:01:51,450
and not necessarily really understanding the type of content that needs to be there and the requirements

27
00:01:51,450 --> 00:01:52,020
that need to be there.

28
00:01:52,020 --> 00:01:56,970
So really consult all those artifacts that you have and if you don't have them, you know, talk to

29
00:01:56,970 --> 00:02:01,470
the right people that can get you that information, whether that be product managers, clients, stakeholders,

30
00:02:01,470 --> 00:02:06,510
internal stakeholders, you know, use your voice if you need those requirements to even start.

31
00:02:06,660 --> 00:02:08,880
So why do we use them?

32
00:02:09,449 --> 00:02:10,560
Two big reasons.

33
00:02:11,039 --> 00:02:16,170
I like using them because they really help to test your concepts and your structure, so they really

34
00:02:16,170 --> 00:02:19,230
help you to understand how users will navigate your product.

35
00:02:19,230 --> 00:02:24,210
Sometimes you can use your wireframes to highlight certain areas that you think need to have prominence

36
00:02:24,210 --> 00:02:29,220
on a page to test if that piece of content is actually working and if the user flow makes sense.

37
00:02:29,220 --> 00:02:34,080
So this is one of the big reasons I use that so that it could be like user flows again, but in much

38
00:02:34,080 --> 00:02:34,950
more detail.

39
00:02:34,950 --> 00:02:39,250
Understanding the different types of interactions and putting it into a wireframe makes it a little

