00:02:39,280 --> 00:02:42,870
more easier to test with users to get, I guess, better results.

41
00:02:43,230 --> 00:02:49,830
The next best thing, actually, I think this is the number one thing actually you need to use them

42
00:02:49,830 --> 00:02:50,430
to learn.

43
00:02:50,430 --> 00:02:53,850
You know, they are fast, cheap and impermanent.

44
00:02:53,850 --> 00:02:55,560
Don't get attached to wireframes.

45
00:02:55,560 --> 00:02:56,670
They're meant to change.

46
00:02:56,670 --> 00:03:02,910
As you gather more information through research and feedback from your clients and from your users,

47
00:03:03,150 --> 00:03:04,770
they're a great place to fail.

48
00:03:04,770 --> 00:03:09,540
And I don't mean that negatively on a project you want to fail as quickly as possible, and that means

49
00:03:09,540 --> 00:03:15,270
you want to test your assumptions as quick as possible before it gets to high fidelity designs or even

50
00:03:15,270 --> 00:03:16,110
development.

51
00:03:16,110 --> 00:03:19,110
You know, they serve as that common language for your team as well.

52
00:03:19,110 --> 00:03:24,150
They're complex enough to inform everyone, but simple enough to not get bogged down by too much detail.

53
00:03:24,180 --> 00:03:28,830
Now, the little kind of graph I have here is the build measure learn graph.

54
00:03:28,830 --> 00:03:34,230
And if anyone's read Lean Startup, I think like that's amazing because it's an amazing book.

55
00:03:34,230 --> 00:03:37,050
But if you haven't, you should definitely read Lean Startup.

56
00:03:37,050 --> 00:03:40,890
It talks a lot about building, measuring and learning.

57
00:03:41,040 --> 00:03:45,930
So what that essentially means is you build and that could be a wireframe, that could be a sketch.

58
00:03:45,960 --> 00:03:47,610
